John,

My read on the ADAS equipment.

The numbers I'm watching:
- We're sending out 24-28 calibrations per month right now to All-Tek over in Clifton
- Each one costs us $420 in their fees plus the lost margin we'd otherwise capture
- We bill the carrier the calibration line at $340 average (varies by carrier and procedure)
- Net out we're losing about $80 per calibration plus the friction of coordinating the handoff

If we bring it in-house:
- 24 calibrations × $340 retained = $8,160/month in captured margin
- Equipment is $85K (Bosch Beissbarth full set)
- Add probably $4K for cert training across the techs
- Payback at current volume: roughly 11 months

What I think tips it pro:
1. The carriers (State Farm, Allstate) are starting to ask whether shops can do calibration in-house. If we can, we get prioritized in their DRP work assignments. If we can't, we don't.
2. Volume is already trending up. As more cars come with ADAS systems (probably 60% of our work in 18 months), the calibration volume will grow.
3. All-Tek is slow. They take 2-3 days. If we do it in-house, we shave 2 days off cycle time, which we bill back as faster turnaround.

Risk:
- The equipment depreciates fast (maybe 5 years before next-gen replacement). At $85K, depreciation alone is $17K/year, which I haven't priced in above.
- If we get the wrong calibration job, the rework cost is high (we'd be on the hook for re-aiming the cameras and any downstream issue).

My vote: cash buy if possible. Financing at 36 months adds $2K/year in interest cost. At our volume that's still worth it but cash buy is cleaner.

Hector
